label.value: abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which actin cytoskeleton organization is abnormal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to 'abnormal actin cytoskeleton' (FYPO:0002398), but note that an abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: abolished actin fusion focus assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which actin fusion focus assembly does not occur. An actin fusion focus normally forms during mating at the site where the two cells will fuse.

label.value: abnormal cell wall organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cell wall organization is abnormal. Cell wall organization results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the fungal-type cell wall.

label.value: incomplete cell wall disassembly at cell fusion site

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the cell wall is broken down to a lesser extent than in wild type at the site of cell-cell fusion during mating.

label.value: narrow cell fusion site following mating

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which the cell is narrower than normal at the point where cell fusion occurred during mating. Normally, the cell expands at the fusion site after fusion takes place.

label.value: increased cellular protein aggregate level during cellular response to heat

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein present as aggregates of misfolded protein is greater than normal during a cellular response to heat.

label.value: decreased duration of heterochromatin maintenance involved in chromatin silencing at centromere outer repeat

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the duration of heterochromatin maintenance is shorter than normal in the context of chromatin silencing at centromere outer repeat regions.

label.value: decreased protein localization to nucleus, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasmic foci

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is decreased, and the protein is instead visible in one or a few foci or dots in the cytoplasm.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal termination of RNA polymerase II transcription

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II is abnormal. Termination of all transcripts, or a subset of transcripts, may be affected.

label.value: abnormal termination of RNA polymerase II transcription at rDNA

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II at sites in ribosomal DNA (rDNA) is abnormal.

definition.value: Although rDNA is normally transcribed by RNA polymerase I, RNA polymerase II mediates antisense transcription in subtelomeric rDNA repeats on chromosome III.

label.value: abnormal termination of RNA polymerase II transcription at tDNA

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II at tRNA genes (tDNA) is abnormal.

definition.value: Although tDNA is normally transcribed by RNA polymerase III, RNA polymerase II mediates antisense transcription at some tRNA genes.

label.value: abnormal termination of RNA polymerase II transcription at highly transcribed protein-coding genes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II at highly transcribed protein-coding genes is abnormal.

label.value: increased rDNA antisense siRNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of siRNA derived from antisense transcription of ribosomal DNA measured in a cell is greater than normal.

label.value: decreased antisense RNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of antisense RNA measured in a cell is lower than normal. Antisense RNA is transcribed from the coding, rather than the template, strand of DNA.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased rDNA antisense small RNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of small RNA (such as siRNA) derived from antisense transcription of ribosomal DNA measured in a cell is lower than normal.

label.value: decreased tDNA antisense small RNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of small RNA (such as siRNA) derived from antisense transcription of transfer RNA genes measured in a cell is lower than normal.

label.value: increased number of Rad52 foci at rDNA replication origins

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of DNA replication origins in ribosomal DNA at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is greater than normal.

label.value: increased number of Rad52 foci at rDNA replication pause sites

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of DNA replication pause sites in ribosomal DNA at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is greater than normal.

label.value: decreased number of Rad52 foci at highly transcribed protein-coding genes

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates at or near highly transcribed protein-coding genes is lower than normal.

label.value: increased number of R-loops at rDNA

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA-DNA hybrid molecules is greater than normal in ribosomal DNA regions.

label.value: abnormal rDNA copy number

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the number of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) repeats present in the rDNA arrays on chromosome III is abnormal (significantly greater or less than the range in wild type cells).

label.value: normal rDNA copy number

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) repeats present in the rDNA arrays on chromosome III is normal (within the range in wild type cells).

label.value: stably decreased rDNA copy number during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) repeats present in the rDNA arrays on chromosome III is significantly lower than the range in wild type cells, but remains at the same level over successive generations.

label.value: progressively decreasing rDNA copy number during successive meiotic generations

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the number of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) repeats present in the rDNA arrays on chromosome III is significantly lower than the range in wild type cells, and continues to decrease over successive meiotic generations (i.e. cycles of mating, meiosis, sporulation, spore germination and vegetative growth).

label.value: inviable vegetative cell with cell death during mitosis

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell dies as it goes through mitosis, usually as a result of abnormal chromosome and spindle dynamics.

label.value: normal protein localization to nucleus during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased phosphatase activity during cellular response to adenine starvation

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a phosphatase activity is decreased during a cellular response to adenine starvation.

label.value: arrested mitotic spindle elongation during anaphase B

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle elongation ends earlier than normal during anaphase B. Elongation stops before the spindle reaches its normal maximum length.

label.value: decreased protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone during anaphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone is decreased during anaphase. The mitotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone during anaphase A

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone during anaphase A does not occur. The mitotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap. Anaphase A is the stage of mitosis in which the kinetochore microtubules shorten as chromosomes move toward the spindle poles.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone during anaphase B

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone is decreased during anaphase B. The mitotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap. Anaphase B is the stage of mitosis in which the polar microtubules elongate and the two poles of the spindle move farther apart.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased phosphatase activity during cellular response to adenine starvation

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a phosphatase activity is increased during a cellular response to adenine starvation.

label.value: abolished protein localization to nucleus during cellular response to hydrogen peroxide

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is abolished during a cellular response to hydrogen peroxide.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein oxidation during cellular response to hydrogen peroxide

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of oxidation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is decreased during a cellular response to hydrogen peroxide.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished cell population growth during glucose starvation

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which a cell population does not grow in a medium containing little or no glucose.

definition.value: Use this term for a population of cells that does not grow under conditions where glucose is absent or limiting (below about 4.4 mM (0.08%)), but does grow using a different carbon source or when more glucose is available (a cell population that does not grow on any media would be considered inviable). Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise. Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to plasma membrane

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in which the localization of a protein to the plasma membrane is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the plasma membrane and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to plasma membrane, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm, during glucose starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in which the localization of a protein to the plasma membrane is abolished when the cell is subject to glucose starvation, and the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term. Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: abnormal high-affinity glucose import

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which high-affinity import of glucose into the cell is abnormal.

label.value: protein mislocalized to nucleus during glucose starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that is not normally found in the nucleus is observed there when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used to annotate any case where a protein is found in the nucleus in a mutant, but not in wild type. In some cases, there may be enough additional information to annotate to 'abnormal protein localization' (FYPO:0000443) or one of its descendants. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term. Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: protein mislocalized to cytoplasm

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in which a protein that is not normally found in the cytoplasm is observed there.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used to annotate any case where a protein is found in the cytoplasm in a mutant, but not in wild type. In some cases, there may be enough additional information to annotate to 'abnormal protein localization' (FYPO:0000443) or one of its descendants. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: multiseptate vegetative cell with binucleate and anucleate compartments

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has two nuclei and more than one septum, and the septa are grouped together between two compartments, one contains both nuclei.

label.value: abnormal mitotic DNA replication lagging strand elongation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which lagging strand elongation during nuclear DNA replication is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal mitotic DNA replication lagging strand elongation at telomere

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which lagging strand elongation during nuclear DNA replication is abnormal at telomeric regions.

label.value: increased number of Rad52 foci at telomeres

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of DNA replication pause sites in telomeric regions at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is greater than normal.

label.value: transcription phenotype

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects DNA-dependent transcription.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: normal protein transport during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein transport is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein metabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a protein metabolic process is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). A protein metabolic process is a series of chemical reactions and pathways involving a specific protein.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: normal RNA metabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a protein metabolic process is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). An RNA metabolic process is a series of chemical reactions and pathways involving any type of RNA.

label.value: abnormal RNA metabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a protein metabolic process is abnormal. An RNA metabolic process is a series of chemical reactions and pathways involving any type of RNA.

label.value: RNA transport phenotype

value.value: A cell process phenotype that affects an RNA transport process.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
